1 NOTE {geni:about_me} Paternal haplogroup I-M438, I-S17250 (23andme.com)
2 CONT ==Biography==
2 CONT '''Leonid HORVATH''' was born on July 27, 1834 in Odesa, Odessa Oblast, Ukraine. His parents were [https://www.geni.com/profile-34639131997 Николай Антонович ХОРВАТ] and [https://www.geni.com/profile-7475362 Lubov Alexandrovna HOR
2 CONC VATH (Pischevich)]. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Born into a family of hereditary nobles of the Kherson province. Father  Leonid Nikolaevich Horvat - was the great-grandson of General I. S. Horvat, who stood at the origins of New Serbia. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Mother - Baroness Maria Pilar von Pilhau - one of the daughters of General Karl Pilar von Pilhau, great-granddaughter of General Field Marshal M.I.Kutuzov. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Nikolai Antonovich HORVAT and Lubov Alexandrovna HORVATH (Pischevich).
2 CONT
2 CONT Leonid married [https://www.geni.com/profile-63045170 Maria HORVATH (Pilar von Pilchau)]. 
2 CONT Together they had the following children: [https://www.geni.com/profile-34639129930 Dimitri Leonidovitch HORVATH]; [https://www.geni.com/profile-34639129983 Vladimir Leonidovitch HORVATH]; [https://www.geni.com/profile-34639129965
2 CONC  Catherine (Ekaterina) SMOLSKI (Horvath)]; [https://www.geni.com/profile-34639131673 Любовь Леонидовна ХОРВАТ]; [https://www.geni.com/profile-34639131696 Ольга Леонидовна ХОРВАТ]. 
2 CONT
2 CONT He died in London, England (United Kingdom). Suicide.
2 CONT
2 CONT https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/192348881/leonid-nikolaevich-horvath
2 CONT ----
2 CONT Origin and Migrations of Haplogroups I-M438   The men of haplogroup I-M438 radiated outward from the Balkans into the eastern half of the continent. Their descendants are found most concentrated in eastern Europe and western Russi
2 CONC a, where they make up 40% of the male population in Bosnia and 30% in Croatia. Some, however, moved farther north and west. Nearly 40% of men on the Mediterranean island of Sardinia carry haplogroup I-M438, and they are also relat
2 CONC ively common in the Netherlands and Germany. Finally, they can also be found in Sweden, particularly in the northern province of Vasterbotten, where their ancestors likely arrived with the more recent migration of German and Dutch
2 CONC  immigrants during the 17th century.
