1 TITL Captain
1 NOTE {geni:about_me} Captain Haskell's Octagon House The octagon house was built in 1847-1848 by the housewright John Vinal for the master of the New Bedford whaler Mercury, Captain Fordyce Dennis Haskell and his wife Sylvia. Bays, oth
2 CONC er additions and architectural embellishments were added in the 1860s by whale oil merchant John Hastings. Now considered a curiosity of American architectural history, the brief craze for the 'Octagon Mode' was inspired by Orson 
2 CONC Squire Fowler, a phrenologist, publisher, pop-psychologist, and all-round Victorian eccentric. Fowler lectured widely on a variety of topics, vigorously promoting his book of octagon plans which went through nine editions between 
2 CONC 1848 and 1860. Octagonal houses were touted as superior in economy of construction, efficiency of space use and ventilation, as well as supposedly enhancing health, happiness and sexual harmony. A century later, the house had fall
2 CONC en into a sorry state of disrepair. The previous owner undertook extensive, painstaking restoration in the 1980s, which are continuing.
2 CONT
2 CONT http://www.haskellfamilyhistory.com/database/3/57112.html
2 CONT
2 CONT The crew of the "Mercury"reported that Captain Haskell appeared to enjoy flogging his men. Even his first mate would plead with him to stop.  The seafaring wife who observed these cruel and unfeeling men at sea observed that these
2 CONC  men seem to "leave their souls at home."  One seaman attributed the overzealous discipline to the limited education of many captains, as well as the crew being too young, visiting depraved places, drinking and  whoring.
2 CONT
2 CONT Druett, Joan, "In the Wake of Madness":  Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill, 2003
