1 NOTE {geni:about_me} Patriot of the American Revolution for MASSACHUSETTS with the rank of SERGEANT.  [http://services.dar.org/Public/DAR_Research/search_adb/?action=full&p_id=A085332  DAR Ancestor # A085332]
2 CONT
2 CONT He served in the Revolutionary War as follows:  Corporal, Captain John Black's company, Colonel Jonathan Brewer's regiment, muster roll dated 8/1/1775; enlisted 4/20/1775; service three months, thirteen days; residence Hutchinson 
2 CONC (also Barre).  Also, late Captain Black's company, Colonel Brewer's regiment, company return (probably 10/1775); also, petition signed by Nye and others, belonging to Captain John Black's company, Colonel Brewer's regiment, asking
2 CONC  for allowances for articles lost in battle at Bunker Hill, 6/17/1775; said Nye claimed compensation for loss of bayonet and belt; amounts allowed by resolve on 5/10/1775.  Also Sergeant, Captain Benjamin Nye's company, Colonel Na
2 CONC than Sparhawk's regiment; engaged 8/21/1777, discharged 8/25/1777; service ten days, travel home (96 mi) included; residence, Barre; company marched to reinforce army at Bennington under General Stark.  Also, same company enlisted
2 CONC  9/26/1777, discharged 10/18/1777; service 29 days, including travel home; company marched under Major Jonas Wilder to reinforce the Northern Army for 30 days.
2 CONT
2 CONT ====================================
2 CONT
2 CONT Soldiers of Oakham, Massachusetts, in the Revolutionary War, the War of 1812 ...
2 CONT By Henry Parks Wright
2 CONT
2 CONT https://books.google.com/books?id=e9yC2GGgXMYC&pg=PA115
2 CONT
2 CONT Ebenezer Nye enlisted for the town of Barre, April 20, 1775, in Capt. John Black's Co., Col. Jonathan Brewer's Regt., and was made Corporal. He was in the battle of Bunker Hill, and received compensation for a bayonet and belt los
2 CONC t in the battle. He went also for the town of Barre in Capt. Benjamin Nye's Co. on the Bennington alarm, August 21, 1777, and again in the same company, on September 26, sent to reinforce the Northern Army. He served for the town 
2 CONC of Oakham in Capt. Jotham Houghton's Co., Col. Samuel Denny's Regt., from October 24 to December 1, 1779, at Claverack, and has credit on the Oakham town records for fifteen days in April, 1777, on an alarm at Williamstown. His na
2 CONC me is on the roll of Capt. Newell's Co. for fifteen days' service, on the march to Enfield, Conn., November 3 to November 18, 1778.
2 CONT
2 CONT Ebenezer Nye came from Barre, and bought in 1778 of John Moore, for £700, two hundred and five acres with buildings thereon, still known as the Crocker Nye farm. He was Selectman of Oakham for nine years, and was a member of the C
2 CONC ommittee of Correspondence, Inspection and Safety in 1779.
2 CONT
2 CONT Deacon Jesse Allen bought at the auction of Timothy Nye's property the gun which Ebenezer Nye carried in the Revolution. It was with the barrel of this gun used as a retort that Rev. David Burt made some of his chemical experiment
2 CONC s when he taught the Oakham High School. The explosion of an ancient charge of powder left in the gun from flintlock days somewhat lessened the enthusiasm of the students for that kind of laboratory practice. The gun is now in the
2 CONC  possession of William A. Nye.
2 CONT
2 CONT Ebenezer Nye was married, July 8, 1759, to Meletiah Sturges of Hyannis, who was born in 1740 and died in March, 1826. Children:
2 CONT
2 CONT Josiah Sturges, a soldier in the Revolutionary Army.
2 CONT
2 CONT Temperance, who married Jonathan Richardson of Barre, November 12, 1778.
2 CONT
2 CONT Lucretia, who married Alpheus Stone in 1781.
2 CONT
2 CONT Marcy, who married Bowman Chaddock, September 5, 1782.
2 CONT
2 CONT Timothy, baptized June 5, 1768, married November 25, 1790, to Parnal, daughter of Deacon Jesse Allen.
2 CONT
2 CONT Meletiah, baptized July 8, 1770, married November 29, 1792, to Rev. Calvin Chaddock, Dartmouth, 1786.
2 CONT
2 CONT Crocker, born July 4, 1772, married May 23, 1799, to Dulcinia, daughter of Major Artemas Howe. He was the father of David H. Nye and the grandfather of William A. Nye.
2 CONT
2 CONT Achsa, called in her father's will the youngest daughter, baptized August 28, 1774, married Eli Haskell of Middleboro November 1, 1797.
2 CONT
2 CONT Salmon, born in 1778, who was graduated from Dartmouth in 1803, studied law in Barnstable, Mass., was admitted to the Common Pleas Court in Barnstable in 1809, and to the Supreme Judicial Court in Plymouth in October, 1812. He was
2 CONC  County Attorney for Barnstable County from 1811 to 1813. He went South in 1818 and died in 1823 in North Carolina.
2 CONT
2 CONT John, born in 1780, who was graduated from Dartmouth in 1801, in the class with Daniel Webster, studied law in Providence and practiced in New Bedford, Mass., where he died in 1826.
2 CONT
2 CONT Ebenezer Nye died in Oakham in 1793.
2 CONT
2 CONT Oakham T. R.. i, 189, 252 [his son, Josiah S. Nye]. M. S. R., xi, 584 (5), (7), 585 (3). Oakham V. R., 40, 89 [Jonathan Richardson = Samuell], 126. N. E. Hist. & Gen. Reg., lvii (1003), 410-414. General Catalogue of Dartmouth Coll
2 CONC ege (1910-11), 210, 212. Letter of Mrs. William A. Nye of Oakham. Wore. Co. Prob. Records. Aug. 6, 1793. Wore. Co. Reg. of Deeds, lxxvi, 338. Rev. D. Tomlinson's Notes. Paige, Hist . of Hardwick, 429, 430. Nye Genealogy, 27, 44, 9
2 CONC 0, 138 [Pamelia Sturges should be Meletiah], 234. Davis, Mass. Bench and Bar, ii, 330 [Julia (Hinckley) should be Meletiah (Sturges)]. Hyannis Town Clerk's Records.
