2 TITL https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Roosevelt-18
1 NOTE He was the first president to exploit the public dimensions of his office 
2 CONT in an age of mass communications, a reform leader at home and a skilled 
2 CONT diplomat abroad. In his lifetime Roosevelt became a personal model, 
2 CONT particularly for the country's youth, in a way that no public figure has 
2 CONT matched. He was one of the most popular presidents in American history. 
2 CONT
2 CONT He was educated by private tutors and studied at Harvard University, 
2 CONT graduating in 1880 as a member of Phi Beta Kappa and the most prestigious 
2 CONT social clubs. Ill health marred his boyhood, and he suffered poor 
2 CONT eyesight, attacks of asthma, and nervous digestion, before teenage 
2 CONT body-building efforts transformed him into a strong, vigorous young man. 
2 CONT After his father's sudden death in 1878, Roosevelt forsook scientific 
2 CONT ambitions, developed political interests. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Early Political Career
2 CONT
2 CONT After graduation from college, Roosevelt entered politics and abandoned 
2 CONT the study of law when, as a Republican, he was elected to the New York 
2 CONT State Assembly in 1881. He attracted immediate attention in the press with 
2 CONT his upper-class background, colorful personality, and bold independence. 
2 CONT In 1884, after serving three years in the Assembly, he left politics 
2 CONT briefly, both from grief at the death of his wife and because he had 
2 CONT alienated the reform wing of his party that year by supporting James G. 
2 CONT Blaine for the presidency. Roosevelt spent the next two years ranching and 
2 CONT hunting in the Dakota Territory, which began his identification with the 
2 CONT Wild West. He continued to write histories, biographies, and magazine 
2 CONT articles, producing more than a dozen books between 1880 and 1900. Back in 
2 CONT politics in 1886, he ran unsuccessfully for mayor of New York City, 
2 CONT campaigned for the national Republican ticket in 1888, and served as Civil 
2 CONT Service commissioner in Washington, D.C., from 1889 to 1895. From 1895 to 
2 CONT 1897, Roosevelt renewed political ties and enhanced his fame with his 
2 CONT energetic, reform-minded service as New York City's police commissioner. 
2 CONT After campaigning for his party's national ticket again in 1896, he became 
2 CONT assistant secretary of the navy and worked to expand and modernize the 
2 CONT navy and get the United States into war with Spain over Cuba. 
2 CONT
2 CONT War Hero and Vice-President
2 CONT
2 CONT The Spanish-American War made Roosevelt a nationally known figure. His 
2 CONT volunteer cavalry regiment, which included both cowboys and aristocrats 
2 CONT like himself, was dubbed the Rough Riders and received extensive press 
2 CONT coverage. Their charge at the Battle of San Juan Hill in Cuba (July 1898) 
2 CONT was the most celebrated exploit of the war. Roosevelt became a popular 
2 CONT hero overnight, and his favorite nickname for the rest of his life was the 
2 CONT Colonel. He reaped a swift political reward when his party's New York 
2 CONT boss, Senator Thomas C. Platt (1833-1910), chose him to run for governor 
2 CONT in the face of scandals that threatened a Republican defeat. Enormous 
2 CONT crowds greeted the candidate wherever he appeared in the 1898 campaign, 
2 CONT and he carried his ticket to a narrow victory. Those crowds and similar 
2 CONT outpourings when Roosevelt traveled west to a Rough Riders' reunion in 
2 CONT 1899 propelled him toward the Republican vice-presidential nomination as 
2 CONT William McKinley's running mate in 1900. Also favoring his nomination was 
2 CONT Senator Platt's desire to get him out of New York. Roosevelt was an 
2 CONT activist, independent governor, who did not submit to the Republican 
2 CONT organization; he responded to popular disquiet over big business and 
2 CONT showed his own concern over conservation of natural resources. Gracefully 
2 CONT although unwillingly submitting to the vice-presidential draft, Roosevelt 
2 CONT demonstrated his energy and popularity again in the 1900 campaign, as he 
2 CONT made whirlwind tours appealing to patriotic memories of the war. He had 
2 CONT little to do as vice-president, but his inactivity ended with McKinley's 
2 CONT assassination in September 1901, when Roosevelt became the youngest 
2 CONT president in U.S. history. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Domestic Policy
2 CONT
2 CONT Roosevelt's entry into the White House changed politics more in mood than 
2 CONT in substance. With his vivid personality, ceaseless activity, young 
2 CONT family, and social glamour, he became a popular idol, a position he 
2 CONT cultivated by careful attention to the press and a flair for the dramatic. 
2 CONT On domestic issues he moved cautiously, probably going little further in 
2 CONT his first term than McKinley would have done. Well-publicized prosecutions 
2 CONT of big businesses earned him acclaim as a trustbuster, and his public 
2 CONT mediation of the anthracite coal strike in 1902 showed sympathies for 
2 CONT labor and consumers. One issue on which he did move boldly was 
2 CONT conservation, both by publicizing it long before any other leader and by 
2 CONT using his presidential powers, often high-handedly, to set aside 125 
2 CONT million acres (about 51 million ha) of western land as national forests. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Roosevelt went further after his triumphant election in 1904. Having 
2 CONT consolidated his position among Republicans, he won the nomination without 
2 CONT opposition and ran on his record, which he called the Square Deal, to win 
2 CONT a big victory over his colorless Democratic opponent, Alton B. Parker 
2 CONT (1852-1926). Roosevelt's second term brought two legislative milestones:  
2 CONT passage of the Hepburn Railway Rate Act of 1905, which strengthened the 
2 CONT powers of the Interstate Commerce Commission, and the Pure Food and Drug 
2 CONT Act of 1906, which established the Food and Drug Administration. He later 
2 CONT advocated further measures to deal with big business and social problems, 
2 CONT but conservative opponents in his own party blocked those proposals. 
2 CONT Roosevelt wielded his political power at home for the last time in 1908 by 
2 CONT picking his friend, Secretary of War William Howard Taft, as his 
2 CONT successor, engineering Taft's nomination and aiding his election to the 
2 CONT presidency. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Foreign Policy
2 CONT
2 CONT Roosevelt pursued an activist foreign policy from the beginning of his 
2 CONT presidency, in keeping with his longtime motto "Speak softly and carry a 
2 CONT big stick." Sometimes he moved quietly and delicately behind the scenes, 
2 CONT as when he fended off possible German intervention in Venezuela in 1902 
2 CONT and when he worked to preserve the European balance of power in a series 
2 CONT of crises between 1904 and 1906. At other times he acted loudly and 
2 CONT bluntly, as when he abetted the 1903 revolution in Panama that led to 
2 CONT United States acquisition of territory for the Panama Canal, and when he 
2 CONT proclaimed that the United States had "police power" over Latin America in 
2 CONT the Roosevelt Corollary to the Monroe Doctrine (1904). He used both public 
2 CONT and private channels in his mediation of the Russo-Japanese War in 1905 
2 CONT which won him the Nobel Peace Prize, the first to go to an American and 
2 CONT when he sent a delegation to the Algeciras Conference of 1906 to help 
2 CONT settle a conflict between Germany and France over the control of Morocco. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Throughout his presidency Roosevelt labored to strengthen and modernize 
2 CONT the armed forces. His secretaries of war, Elihu Root and Taft, introduced 
2 CONT the general staff system to the army and streamlined reserve methods. The 
2 CONT navy remained a special concern with Roosevelt, and he harried Congress, 
2 CONT with partial success, to build more battleships and cruisers. In 1907 he 
2 CONT sent America's battle fleet on a voyage around the world, both to impress 
2 CONT Japan during a controversy over exclusion of Oriental immigrants and to 
2 CONT display the nation's new naval prowess. At the same time, he dispatched 
2 CONT Taft to negotiate agreements that appeased Japanese interests in Manchuria 
2 CONT and helped defuse the dispute over immigration. Roosevelt left a record of 
2 CONT strong diplomacy usually tempered by sensitivity and restraint, and he 
2 CONT made his last public appearance as president in February 1909, when he 
2 CONT reviewed the fleet returning from its world cruise. 
2 CONT
2 CONT Third Party Leader
2 CONT
2 CONT Stepping down from office at the age of 50, younger than most other 
2 CONT presidents have been when first elected, Roosevelt went abroad for more 
2 CONT than a year, first on a hunting and nature-study safari to Africa and then 
2 CONT on a spectacular tour of the European capitals. On his return home in the 
2 CONT summer of 1910 he quickly became embroiled in factional fights among 
2 CONT Republicans and slowly but steadily became estranged from his successor. 
2 CONT Roosevelt finally broke with Taft both because he could not abide the new 
2 CONT president's inept handling of the split between progressive and 
2 CONT conservative Republicans and because he resented his own loss of power. 
2 CONT Assuming command of the progressives and advocating farther-reaching 
2 CONT economic and social reforms, Roosevelt contested the 1912 Republican 
2 CONT presidential nomination, winning most of the primaries but losing at the 
2 CONT convention to the same presidential party control he had earlier used to 
2 CONT nominate Taft. Charging that he had been cheated of the nomination, 
2 CONT Roosevelt bolted to run as the candidate of the hastily formed Progressive 
2 CONT party. When he was wounded in an assassination attempt in Milwaukee, 
2 CONT Wisconsin (October 1912), he made light of it, saying, "It takes more than 
2 CONT that to kill a bull moose." Thereafter, the Progressives were nicknamed 
2 CONT the Bull Moose party. Roosevelt outpolled Taft "a tribute to his abiding 
2 CONT popularity" but his hopes of winning and establishing a new major party 
2 CONT were thwarted. The Democratic nominee, Woodrow Wilson, who also appealed 
2 CONT to progressives, carried the election. 
2 CONT
2 CONT World War I
2 CONT
2 CONT After his 1912 defeat, Roosevelt spent the last six years of his life in 
2 CONT mounting frustration, first over Wilson's enactment of much of his reform 
2 CONT program, then over American neutrality after the outbreak of World War I 
2 CONT in 1914, and finally over his own failure to be allowed to raise a 
2 CONT division to fight in France after the United States entered the war in 
2 CONT 1917. Although he continued to advocate domestic reforms, he increasingly 
2 CONT devoted himself to calling for a strong pro-Allied foreign policy and 
2 CONT greater military preparedness. Roosevelt was gradually reconciled with his 
2 CONT former party opponents, including Taft. He disbanded the Progressives in 
2 CONT 1916 to back the Republican nominee against Wilson, and it seemed certain 
2 CONT that he would be the party's candidate in 1920. His four sons all fought 
2 CONT in World War I, and the death of the youngest, Quentin, in combat as an 
2 CONT aviator in August 1918, was a heavy blow. Roosevelt's health deteriorated 
2 CONT during the final years of his life, partly as a result of tropical fevers 
2 CONT contracted on an expedition to the Amazon region of Brazil in 1914.
1 NOTE Theodore Roosevelt
2 CONT http://trees.ancestry.com/rd?f=image&guid=337b0033-ca54-44ba-9c82-0c27cf0e85cc&tid=261097&pid=-1976498699
1 NOTE Teddy Roosevelt
2 CONT http://trees.ancestry.com/rd?f=image&guid=76d370f3-5989-4635-8574-8e5d017bb4ab&tid=261097&pid=-1976498699
1 NOTE Name Prefix:<NPFX> President 
2 CONT Name Suffix:<NSFX> JR.
1 NOTE <tpphoto><id>2414099</id></tpphoto>
1 NOTE  With the assassination of President McKinley, Theodore Roosevelt, not quite 43, became the youngest President in the Nation's history. He brought new excitement and power to the Presidency, as he vigorously led Congress and the A
2 CONC merican public toward progressive reforms and a strong foreign policy.
2 CONT
2 CONT He took the view that the President as a "steward of the people" should take whatever action necessary for the public good unless expressly forbidden by law or the Constitution." I did not usurp power," he wrote, "but I did greatl
2 CONC y broaden the use of executive power."
2 CONT
2 CONT Roosevelt's youth differed sharply from that of the log cabin Presidents. He was born in New York City in 1858 into a wealthy family, but he too struggled--against ill health--and in his triumph became an advocate of the strenuous
2 CONC  life.
2 CONT
2 CONT In 1884 his first wife, Alice Lee Roosevelt, and his mother died on the same day. Roosevelt spent much of the next two years on his ranch in the Badlands of Dakota Territory. There he mastered his sorrow as he lived in the saddle,
2 CONC  driving cattle, hunting big game--he even captured an outlaw. On a visit to London, he married Edith Carow in December 1886.
2 CONT
2 CONT During the Spanish-American War, Roosevelt was lieutenant colonel of the Rough Rider Regiment, which he led on a charge at the battle of San Juan. He was one of the most conspicuous heroes of the war.
2 CONT
2 CONT Boss Tom Platt, needing a hero to draw attention away from scandals in New York State, accepted Roosevelt as the Republican candidate for Governor in 1898. Roosevelt won and served with distinction.
2 CONT
2 CONT As President, Roosevelt held the ideal that the Government should be the great arbiter of the conflicting economic forces in the Nation, especially between capital and labor, guaranteeing justice to each and dispensing favors to n
2 CONC one.
2 CONT
2 CONT Roosevelt emerged spectacularly as a "trust buster" by forcing the dissolution of a great railroad combination in the Northwest. Other antitrust suits under the Sherman Act followed.
2 CONT
2 CONT Roosevelt steered the United States more actively into world politics. He liked to quote a favorite proverb, "Speak softly and carry a big stick. . . . "
2 CONT
2 CONT Aware of the strategic need for a shortcut between the Atlantic and Pacific, Roosevelt ensured the construction of the Panama Canal. His corollary to the Monroe Doctrine prevented the establishment of foreign bases in the Caribbea
2 CONC n and arrogated the sole right of intervention in Latin America to the United States.
2 CONT
2 CONT He won the Nobel Peace Prize for mediating the Russo-Japanese War, reached a Gentleman's Agreement on immigration with Japan, and sent the Great White Fleet on a goodwill tour of the world.
2 CONT
2 CONT Some of Theodore Roosevelt's most effective achievements were in conservation. He added enormously to the national forests in the West, reserved lands for public use, and fostered great irrigation projects.
2 CONT
2 CONT He crusaded endlessly on matters big and small, exciting audiences with his high-pitched voice, jutting jaw, and pounding fist. "The life of strenuous endeavor" was a must for those around him, as he romped with his five younger c
2 CONC hildren and led ambassadors on hikes through Rock Creek Park in Washington, D.C.
2 CONT
2 CONT Leaving the Presidency in 1909, Roosevelt went on an African safari, then jumped back into politics. In 1912 he ran for President on a Progressive ticket. To reporters he once remarked that he felt as fit as a bull moose, the name
2 CONC  of his new party.
2 CONT
2 CONT While campaigning in Milwaukee, he was shot in the chest by a fanatic. Roosevelt soon recovered, but his words at that time would have been applicable at the time of his death in 1919: "No man has had a happier life than I have le
2 CONC d; a happier life in every way."
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT President's Day U.S. Presidents: United in Service
2 CONT Take a look at presidential biographies made by kids and videos about service from the President's Council on Service and Civic Participation.
2 CONT
2 CONT Twenty-Sixth President
2 CONT 1901-1909
2 CONT
2 CONT Born: October 27, 1858 in New York, New York
2 CONT
2 CONT Died: January 6, 1919 in Oyster Bay, New York
2 CONT
2 CONT Married to Edith Kermit Carow
