1 NAME Thomas H. /Nye/
2 GIVN Thomas H.
2 _MARNM Nye
1 SEX M
1 BIRT
2 DATE 9 NOV 1804
2 ADDR
3 CITY New Bedford
3 STAE Massachusetts
3 CTRY United States
1 OCCU President
2 DATE 1861
2 PLAC Bank of Commerce
2 ADDR
3 CITY New Bedford
3 STAE MA
3 CTRY United States
1 DEAT
2 DATE 22 MAR 1882
2 ADDR
3 CITY New Bedford
3 STAE Massachusetts
3 CTRY United States
1 OCCU Bank President
1 NOTE {geni:about_me} He was Representative in 1850.
2 CONT
2 CONT He lived in New Bedford and was a whaling and banking tycoon.  He lived in a mansion he built around 1833 with a panoramic view of the bay.  The mansion had 14 rooms and many costly furnishings, which he had collected in his trave
2 CONC ls around the world.  His business partner was his younger brother Asa Russell Nye.
2 CONT
2 CONT He served in the Revolutionary Army.
2 CONT
2 CONT ___________________________________
2 CONT
2 CONT During the terrible winter of 1856, the packet ship "John Rutledge" was en route from Liverpool when a piece of floating ice knocked a hole in her hull.   Cargo was jettisoned and the pumps were worked to capacity, but the vessel 
2 CONC continued to sink.  One hundred and fifty passengers and crew had to abandon the ship.  
2 CONT
2 CONT Thomas Nye was one of them.  According to the Boston globe, Nov 15, 1925, he was "cooler than most."  Before he got into the open boat he put on two suits of clothes.  The demijohn of water for emergency use was smashed as his boa
2 CONC t was being launched; in a few days his group was dying of thirst.  He was"the only one to resist the temptation to drink salt water."  Some snow fell, and he obtained moisture from that.  After nine days, the "Germania" found him
2 CONC  lying in the boat " with the ghostly companionship of the dead," the only person still alive.
2 CONT
2 CONT When rescued, he weighed only 65 lbs. and several of his frostbitten toes had to be amputated, but he survived.
2 CONT
2 CONT 19th Century Seafarers, Nye, George P Nye; The Nye Family of America Association, Inc. publisher, 1993
