1 NAME Nicholas /Longworth/ III
2 GIVN Nicholas
2 NSFX III
2 _MARNM Longworth
1 NAME Nicholas Longworth, III, 38th Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives
1 SEX M
1 BURI
2 PLAC Spring Grove Cemetery
2 ADDR
3 CITY Cincinnati
3 STAE Ohio
3 CTRY United States
1 BIRT
2 DATE 5 NOV 1869
2 ADDR
3 CITY Cincinnati
3 STAE Ohio
3 CTRY United States
1 DEAT
2 DATE 9 APR 1931
2 ADDR
3 CITY Aiken
3 STAE South Carolina
3 CTRY United States
1 OCCU speaker of the House
1 TITL Rep.
1 NOTE {geni:about_me} Nicolas Longworth was Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives from 1925 until his death in 1931.
2 CONT
2 CONT ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2 CONT
2 CONT http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_Longworth
2 CONT
2 CONT Nicholas Longworth IV (November 5, 1869 – April 9, 1931) was a prominent American politician in the Republican Party during the first few decades of the 20th century. He served as House Majority Leader from 1923 to 1925 and subseq
2 CONC uently as Speaker of the United States House of Representatives from 1925 to 1931.
2 CONT
2 CONT Early years and education
2 CONT
2 CONT Nicholas was the only son of Nicholas Longworth II (June 16, 1844 – Jan 18, 1890) and Susan Walker. The Longworths were an old, prominent, and wealthy family which dominated Cincinnati. Nicholas Longworth II was the son of Joseph 
2 CONC Longworth and the grandson of Nicholas Longworth, both distinguished citizens of Cincinnati. He graduated from Harvard University in 1866, studied law with his uncle Rufus King, and passed the bar in the spring of 1869. He was an 
2 CONC active member of the bar and briefly served on the Supreme Court of Ohio, but he resigned this position and retired from the practice of law in 1883 upon his father’s death.  He and Susan Walker, a daughter of Judge Timothy Walker
2 CONC , a founding faculty and Dean of the Cincinnati Law School, were married on October 2, 1866.
2 CONT
2 CONT Nicholas Longworth attended the Franklin School, a school for boys in Cincinnati, and then went on to attend Harvard College {Class of 1891}, where he was a member of Delta Kappa Epsilon (Alpha chapter) and the Porcellian Club. He
2 CONC  was a talented, but not necessarily an industrious student; one friend wrote about him: “His good head made it easy for him to get perfectly respectable marks without doing much of any work.” After receiving his bachelor's degree
2 CONC  from Harvard, he attended Harvard Law School for one year, but transferred to and received his law degree from Cincinnati Law School in 1894.
2 CONT
2 CONT A gifted musician, Longworth was considered by Efrem Zimbalist and others as one of the most talented amateur violinists in the United States. In a letter to his sister Clara Leopold Stokowski wrote "Your brother had a rare unders
2 CONC tanding of music. He penetrated directly into the spirit of music. It was his natural element." It is widely rumored that Longworth owned a Stradivarius which his wife Alice later burned in the fireplace. The violin, however, was 
2 CONC just a very good copy of a Stradivarius and was not harmed. After he died, the violin was lent to up-and-coming artists. He also sang and played piano, which made him a welcome parlor guest.
2 CONT
2 CONT Professional life and entry into politics
2 CONT
2 CONT Longworth began a law practice in Cincinnati after being admitted to the Ohio bar in 1894. His political career began with a position on the city's Board of Education in 1898.
2 CONT
2 CONT As the protégé of Republican boss George Cox, Longworth was elected to the Ohio General Assembly, serving in the Ohio House of Representatives in 1899 and 1900, then in the State Senate from 1901 to 1903. In 1902 he was instrument
2 CONC al in writing and passing the Longworth Act, a bill regulating the issuance of municipal bonds, which has been labeled "one of the most successful laws in Ohio's history" Longworth was elected to the United States House of Represe
2 CONC ntatives from the First Congressional District of Ohio which included the city of Cincinnati and counties bordering Kentucky and Indiana.
2 CONT
2 CONT The new representative, still a bachelor, quickly became a popular bon vivant in Washington, D.C. society. He successfully wooed Alice Roosevelt, the daughter of President Theodore Roosevelt; they married in a White House ceremony
2 CONC  in 1906.
2 CONT
2 CONT Already well-known for his social success, Longworth first came to political prominence in 1910, when he led the successful Republican revolt against the autocratic rule of House Speaker Joseph G. Cannon. Throughout his political 
2 CONC career, Longworth was a workhorse, especially on issues regarding foreign affairs and the protective tariff.
2 CONT
2 CONT As the insurgent (or "Progressive") Republicans pulled apart from the conservatives in 1910–12, Longworth sided with the conservatives. Theodore Roosevelt, Longworth's father-in-law, led the Progressives, and bolted the Republican
2 CONC  convention in the 1912 election to set up a third party. However, many of Roosevelt's closest political allies, including Longworth, supported conservative standard-bearer President William Howard Taft. Longworth's decision cause
2 CONC d a permanent chill in his marriage to Roosevelt's daughter, Alice. For men like Longworth expecting a future in politics, bolting the Republican party ticket was simply too radical a step. Also, Longworth agreed more with Taft th
2 CONC an Roosevelt on critical issues like an independent judiciary and support for business.
2 CONT
2 CONT Because the Progressive Party ran a candidate in his district, Longworth was defeated (by only 105 votes) in 1912. (Longworth's wife appeared at a speech by his Progressive opponent and would thereafter joke that it was she who co
2 CONC st her husband at least 100 of those 105 votes.)
2 CONT
2 CONT Majority leader and Speaker of the House
2 CONT
2 CONT Longworth returned to Congress in 1914, serving until his death, and became Majority Leader of the House in 1923.
2 CONT
2 CONT After an effective term as Majority Leader, Longworth moved up to become Speaker in 1925 after Frederick Gillett took a seat in the United States Senate. Ironically, his first act as speaker was to restore much of the power to the
2 CONC  office that had been stripped away during the revolt he had led against Cannon.
2 CONT
2 CONT Longworth began his tenure by punishing 13 self-styled Progressives, who supported Robert LaFollette instead of Calvin Coolidge in 1924. He expelled the rebels from the GOP caucus, and stripped even the committee chairmen among th
2 CONC em of all seniority. Longworth took control of the Steering Committee and Committee on Committees and placed his own men on the Rules Committee, guaranteeing that he controlled the work of the House.
2 CONT
2 CONT Ignoring the left wing of the party, Longworth passed legislation that aimed for balanced budgets and major tax reductions, resisting any new programs that would expand the role of government. However, Longworth defied President H
2 CONC erbert Hoover in 1931 by supporting the long-stalled veterans bonus bill; it passed but Hoover vetoed it, setting up the Bonus March of 1932.
2 CONT
2 CONT Longworth reached across the aisle to Democrats, forging a productive relationship with John Nance Garner, that party's House minority leader, who relied upon informal methods to strengthen his party's influence. He enjoyed a clos
2 CONC e rapport with Garner, who said of Longworth, "I was the heathen and Nick was the aristocrat." Together they hosted a daily gathering of Democratic and Republican congressmen in a secluded room in the Capitol, which became known a
2 CONC s the "Bureau of Education." This unofficial club provided a place for politicians to relax with a drink and get to know and work with one another across party lines.
2 CONT
2 CONT Final days and death
2 CONT
2 CONT Longworth served as speaker until 1931, after the Republicans lost their House majority in the election of 1930. Journalist Frank R. Kent of the Baltimore Sun wrote of him:
2 CONT
2 CONT  "Without any revision of the rules he completely recovered the power of the speakership and was the undisputed leader of the House with as autocratic control as either Reed or Cannon. It is true he exercised this power with infin
2 CONC itely more tact and grace and gumption and without that touch of offensive arrogance that characterized former House Czars. But he was just as much a Czar. What Mr. Longworth clearly proved was this matter of leadership depends no
2 CONC t so much on the rules but on the man.
2 CONT
2 CONT While visiting his friend Dwight Filley Davis (of Davis Cup fame), and Daniel J. Duckett in Aiken, South Carolina, Longworth caught pneumonia and died unexpectedly. His wife Alice brought his body back to Cincinnati, where it was 
2 CONC interred in the Spring Grove Cemetery. At a memorial service held at the Library of Congress on May 3, 1931, his old friends Efrem Zimbalist and Harold Bauer played Brahms's D minor sonata.
2 CONT
2 CONT Character
2 CONT
2 CONT One historian sums up Longworth: "Debonair and aristocratic, given to wearing spats and carrying a gold-headed cane, he was anything but a typical politician. He was perpetually cheerful, quick with a joke or witty retort, and unf
2 CONC ailingly friendly. He seemed never to have a care and made hard decisions with such ease and detachment that some people wondered if anything at all really mattered to him." 
2 CONT
2 CONT One particular famous retort is told about Longworth. One day, while lounging in a chair at the Capitol, another member of the House ran his hand over Longworth's bald pate and commented, "Nice and smooth. Feels just like my wife'
2 CONC s bottom." Longworth felt his own head and returned an answer: "Yes, so it does."
2 CONT
2 CONT Legacy
2 CONT
2 CONT Nicholas Longworth strengthened the power of the House of Representatives. He was popular on both sides of the aisle, and his years of leadership are commemorated in the Longworth House Office Building on Capitol Hill.
2 CONT
2 CONT In the 66 years following his tenure as Speaker of the House, no other Republican served consecutive terms as Speaker until Newt Gingrich was re-elected after the 1996 election.
2 CONT
2 CONT In 2011, John Boehner became the first Ohioan since Longworth to serve as Speaker of the House.
2 CONT
2 CONT Besides his widow, Longworth left one child, Paulina.
