1 TITL Princess
1 NOTE {geni:about_me} House number 3 on Vladimirskaja Street was named "Troubetzkoy House". People talk various things: that there were Decembrists in it and that Sergei Petrovich Troubetzkoy, one of the ideologists of Decabrism, an uns
2 CONC uccessful dictator of the uprising who came to Kiev in 1857, was staying here, and that from the 1960s the house belonged to his family.
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT In fact, a two-story house with a mezzanine - "the ground floor is made of stone, the mezzanine and the mezzanine are made of wood" - built in the 1820s on the orders of the Kursk landowner Alexander Semenovich Annenkov, who owned
2 CONC  a vast estate occupying the entire Andreevskaya Street (now Vladimirskaya Street from the church St. Andrew to Bolszaj Żytomirsk). When designing the building, one of the variants of the façade was used, which is obligatory for u
2 CONC rban planning in the period of Classicism.
2 CONT In 1856, part of the property with house number 3 (in modern numbering) was sold to the court counselor Bonifatsa Vasilyevich Klimovich. The new owner added two symmetrical wings to the house from the side of the courtyard.
2 CONT
2 CONT Currently, the building is one of the few examples of wooden urban buildings of the Classicist era. The floors in the house are flat beam, side vestibules with wooden stairs connect both floors. A corridor enfilade was planned, wi
2 CONC th the separation of representative rooms and planning of an independent entrance to the mezzanine through stairs open from the courtyard side. Large windows with vertical proportions on the second floor, highlighted with wooden f
2 CONC rames. On the second floor, a balcony on metal consoles. The façade design uses the technique of contrasting smooth plastered walls and wooden details (window frames, window sill, frieze, cornice, triangular mezzanine pediment).
2 CONT
2 CONT In July 1867, the house was purchased by twenty-year-old '''Elizaveta Ivanovna Troubetzkaya''' (1847-1915), daughter of Ivan Yakovlevich Lukasevich and Varvara Gavrilovna Vishnevskaya, head of the nobility of the Zolotonosha distr
2 CONC ict of the Kiev province. She became Trubiecko in April 1866, after marrying the ruler of the chancellery of the Institute of Noble Virgins, cadet-cadet of Prince Piotr Aleksandrowicz Troubetzkoy (1833-1893), nephew of the Decembr
2 CONC ist.
2 CONT
2 CONT Father of Piotr Aleksandrowicz - Aleksander Petrovich Troubetzkoy (1792-1853) - participant in the Patriotic War, colonel in the regiment of Siemionowski Life Guards, in 1820 he was transferred to the Dragons' regiment in Kiev. Af
2 CONC ter December 1825 he was under secret surveillance. Two years later, the chief of gendarmes A.Kh. Benckendorff wrote to the governor of Kiev I.G. Kovalev: "I have heard rumors that the retired Colonel Prince Troubetzkoy living in 
2 CONC Kiev is making indecent statements at the expense of the Sovereign Emperor and the Government. Therefore, I am asking for vigilant supervision over him." According to the instructions, all supervised movements and meetings were mo
2 CONC nitored. In particular, the police chief reported that A.P. Troubetzkoy met with Count N.A. Samoilov and went to Smila, to the estate of the latter.
2 CONT
2 CONT Troubetzkoy coat of arms
2 CONT
2 CONT In the 1870s, the Troubetzkoy family discovered in their property the remains of a unique structure from the second half of the 12th century. - rotunda. It was then that the name "Troubetzkoya House", as they say, "went to the mas
2 CONC ses." The fact is that until 1898 the numbering of Kiev buildings was either absent or very confusing. Therefore, when mentioning a house, it was easier to give not its number, but the name of the owner. So it turned out that the 
2 CONC address of the new opening - the rotunda - was listed as "Troubetzkoy house".
2 CONT
2 CONT The rotunda was not fully explored until 1975–1976, when the foundations of the structure were dug under the direction of archaeologists Aleksander Jarosławowicz Borowski and Piotr Pietrowicz Tołoczko. Inside the rotunda there was
2 CONC  a round hall with a diameter of 16 m and a height of 9-10 m. In the center of the room there was a round pillar on which the ceilings rested. Most likely, the building served as a representative prince's hall. But some researcher
2 CONC s believe that it was a religious building: the Catholic Church of St. Mary, or the annalistic Basil's Church in Nowy Dwór, or the Church of Catherine. There are many indications that the rotunda was renovated in the 14th century.
2 CONC  The discovered coins of Włodzimierz Olgerdowicz and Byzantine seals prove that at that time he was "in working condition". Later, when the administrative center moved to Podolia, the rotunda was abandoned and local residents took
2 CONC  it away for building materials.
2 CONT
2 CONT Until recently, the contours of the foundations of the rotunda were lined with bricks. Now the site has been absorbed by school number 25, there is a sports ground on the site of the ancient building.
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT In addition to the rotunda, Borovsky and Tolochko were waiting for another discovery: the remains of a pagan temple from the 10th century. And considering this find, a version of the rotunda's iconic target has a right to exist.
2 CONT
2 CONT In the years 1970-1976, under the supervision of the architect T. Shamenko, "Troubetzkoy House" was examined and restored. Currently, it houses branches of the Institute of Archeology of the National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine
2 CONC .
2 CONT
2 CONT Sources: 
2 CONT
2 CONT 1. Kovalinsky V.V., Kavatskaya T.L. Pushkin in Kiev. - K .: Kiy - 1999 - page 317 
2 CONT 2. Star of memorials of history and culture of Ukraine. Encyclopedic view of twenty-eight volumes. Kiev. Kn 1. Part 1. A – L Editorial editor P. Tronko. - K .: Head of the editorial office to the Star of the Memorials of the Histo
2 CONC ry and Culture of Ukraine under the Ukrainian Encyclopedia im. M.R. Bazhana - 1999 - 580 p.
2 CONT 3. Internet resource "Nostalgia. Kiev. A walk in the old city"
2 CONT 4. Internet resource "Visicom-cards"
2 CONT 5. Internet forum for the post "Ancient Kiev. What? Where? When? (Part 2)" 
